## Alarming Trends in Food Safety Recalls

So far this year, a total of **302 food item recalls** have been reported, marking a significant uptick from previous years. Out of these, **84 have been classified as Class I recalls**, the most severe category where there's a reasonable probability that the use of or exposure to the product will cause serious adverse health consequences or death. To put that in perspective, almost one out of every three recalls posed a potentially life-threatening risk.

## Repeat Offenders and Notable Names

Among the top contributors to these statistics, a few brands stand out. For instance:
- **Moonlight Packing Corporation** had 11 recalls, all classified as Class I. This disconcerting track record earns them a worrisome "F" grade.
- **Albertsons Companies LLC**, with a recall count of 11, including 10 Class I, also scored "F".
- Brands like **CHETAK NEW YORK LLC** and **Made Fresh Salads Inc** exhibit high recall rates with all their incidents being Class I as well. The frequency and severity of their recalls make them brands to keep a watchful eye on.

## Recent Highlights from the Food Recall List

Looking at the **most recent recalls**, reported on **April 8, 2026**, we find:
- **The Maros Group, LLC** had two Class II recalls for undeclared milk in their Prickly Pear Jelly and sulfite contamination in their salad dressing.
- **Lone Star Dairy Products LLC** issued a Class I recall for Salmonella contamination in Spray Dried Dairy Powder, a serious health risk.
- **Super World Trading Inc.** faced a Class III recall for their peanuts containing banned sweeteners, raising concerns about compliance with food additive regulations.

## Areas to Watch

With **173 cases** of allergen-related recalls, this category remains the predominant issue. Salmonella and listeria follow closely, both of which have the potential for significant health impacts. Consumers should exercise caution when purchasing products and opt for brands with clean records when possible.

## Closing Thoughts

The food industry is clearly grappling with challenges to ensure the safety of their products. Consumers must stay informed and vigilant to protect themselves against potential hazards. At Shelf Check, we'll continue to monitor the situation and provide insights to help you make safer choices at the grocery aisle.
